    Protostome and Deuterostome

   Coelomates fall into either protostomes or deuterostomes, depending on how their embryos
   develop, as shown in Figure 5. Protostomes (from the Greek meaning literally "first mouth") are
   coelomates whose embryonic development makes a blastopore (the first opening in the blastula)
   that later develops into a mouth. Deuterostomes ("second mouth") are coelomates whose embryonic
   development produces a blastopore that later forms an anus, with a second opening forming the
   mouth (hence the designation of "second mouth"). Vertebrates are deuterostomes.

   Figure 5. Differences in cleavage between the embryos of protostomes and deuterostomes. Images
